{"title_page": "1905\u201306 British Home Championship", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox international football competition\n|tourney_name=1905\u20131906 British Home Championship\n|image      =\n|size       =\n|caption    =\n|country    =England, Ireland, Scotland and Wales\n|dates      =17 February\u20137 April 1906\n|num_teams  =4\n|champion_other=Shared: {{fb|ENG}}/{{fb|SCO}}\n|attendance =\n|matches    =6\n|goals      =20\n|top_scorer ={{fbicon|WAL|1807}} [[William Green (footballer)|William Green]] and {{fbicon|IRE}} [[Harold Sloan]] {{nowrap|(3 goals)}}\n|prevseason =[[1904\u201305 British Home Championship|1904\u20131905]]\n|nextseason =[[1905\u201306 British Home Championship|1906\u201307]]\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\nThe '''1905\u201306 [[British Home Championship]]''' was the 22nd edition of the annual international [[football (soccer)|football]] tournament played between the British [[Home Nations]]. The trophy was shared between the two sides which regularly dominated the competition, [[England national football team|England]] and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] who each gained four points.\n\nEngland and [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] began the tournament in February 1906, with England scoring five goals without reply and rising to the head of the table. [[Wales national football team|Wales]] joined them after their match with Scotland which they won in [[Edinburgh]] 2\u20130. Scotland recovered to beat Ireland by a single goal and England then moved ahead by beating Wales with an identical scoreline. Playing for lower rankings, Wales and Ireland fought out a thrilling 4\u20134 draw in [[Cardiff]] before the deciding game between England and Scotland. England needed only a draw to take the trophy undisputed, but Scotland played well and in flowing match triumphed 2\u20131 to share the honours.\n\nParts of the Wales vs Ireland match at Wrexham were filmed by the Blackburn company of Mitchell and Kenyon, and is now the oldest surviving footage of an international football match.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=John |editor1-last=Davies|editor1-link=John Davies (historian)|editor2-first=Nigel |editor2-last=Jenkins | editor2-link=Nigel Jenkins| editor3-first=Baines |editor3-last=Menna|editor4-first=Peredur I. |editor4-last=Lynch|title=The Welsh Academy Encyclopaedia of Wales |year=2008 |publisher=University of Wales Press |location=Cardiff|page=282 |isbn=978-0-7083-1953-6}}</ref>\n\n==Table==\n<onlyinclude>{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|show_positions=n\n|winpoints=2\n\n|team1=ENG|name_ENG={{fb|ENG}}\n|team2=SCO|name_SCO={{fb|SCO}}\n|team3=WAL|name_WAL={{fb|WAL|1807}}\n|team4=IRE|name_IRE={{fb|IRE}}\n|win_ENG=2|draw_ENG=0|loss_ENG=1|gf_ENG=7|ga_ENG=2|status_ENG=C\n|win_SCO=2|draw_SCO=0|loss_SCO=1|gf_SCO=3|ga_SCO=3|status_SCO=C\n|win_WAL=1|draw_WAL=1|loss_WAL=1|gf_WAL=6|ga_WAL=5\n|win_IRE=0|draw_IRE=1|loss_IRE=2|gf_IRE=4|ga_IRE=10\n|status_text_C=Co-champions\n|col_C=#ccffcc|text_C=\n|result1=C|result2=C\n|update=complete|source=\n|class_rules = 1) points. The points system worked as follows: 2 points for a win and 1 point for a draw.\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Results==\n{{football box \n | date = 17 February 1906\n | team1 = {{fb-rt|IRE}}\n | score = 0 \u2013 5\n | team2 = {{fb|ENG}}\n | goals1 = &nbsp; \n | goals2 = {{goal|26||89|}} [[Dicky Bond]] <br />{{goal|32}} [[Arthur Brown (footballer, born 1885)|Arthur Brown]] <br />{{goal|56}} [[Stanley Harris (footballer)|Stanley Harris]] <br />{{goal|70}} [[Samuel Day (sportsman)|Samuel Day]]\n | stadium = [[Solitude (football ground)|Solitude]], [[Belfast]] \n | attendance = 14,063\n | referee = Tom Robertson ([[Scottish Football Association|Scotland]])\n}}\n----\n{{football box \n | date = 3 March 1906\n | team1 = {{fb-rt|SCO}}\n | score = 0 \u2013 2\n | team2 = {{fb|WAL|1807}}\n | goals1 = &nbsp; \n | goals2 = {{goal|50}} [[Lot Jones]]<br />{{goal|65}} [[John Love Jones]]\n | stadium = [[Tynecastle Stadium|Tynecastle Park]], [[Edinburgh]] \n | attendance = 25,000\n | referee = John Lewis ([[The Football Association|England]])\n}}\n----\n{{football box \n | date = 17 March 1906\n | team1 = {{fb-rt|IRE}}  \n | score = 0 \u2013 1\n | team2 = {{fb|SCO}}\n | goals1 = &nbsp; \n | goals2 = {{goal|52}} [[Thomas Fitchie]]\n | stadium = [[Dalymount Park]], [[Dublin]] \n | attendance = 8,000\n | referee = Frederick Bye ([[The Football Association|England]])\n}}\n----\n{{football box \n | date = 19 March 1906\n | team1 = {{fb-rt|WAL|1807}}\n | score = 0 \u2013 1\n | team2 = {{fb|ENG}}\n | goals1 = &nbsp; \n | goals2 = {{goal|86}} [[Samuel Day (sportsman)|Samuel Day]]\n | stadium = [[Cardiff Arms Park]], [[Cardiff]] \n | attendance = 15,000\n | referee = Robert Murray ([[Scottish Football Association|Scotland]])\n}}\n----\n{{football box \n | date = 2 April 1906\n | team1 = {{fb-rt|WAL|1807}}\n | score = 4 \u2013 4\n | team2 = {{fb|IRE}}\n | goals1 = {{goal|13||20||28}} [[William Green (footballer)|William Green]] <br />{{goal|55}} [[Hugh Morgan-Owen]]\n | goals2 = {{goal|10||25||74|}} [[Harold Sloan]]<ref name=\"EUF\">{{cite web |title=Wales vs Ireland, 2 April 1906 |url=https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=4494 |website=EU-Football |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> <br />{{goal|72|}} [[Jimmy Maxwell (footballer)|Jimmy Maxwell]]\n | stadium = [[Racecourse Ground]], [[Wrexham]] \n | attendance = 5,000\n | referee = Fred Kirkham ([[The Football Association|England]])\n}}\n----\n{{football box \n | date = 7 April 1906\n | team1 = {{fb-rt|SCO}}\n | score = 2 \u2013 1\n | team2 = {{fb|ENG}}\n | goals1 = [[James Howie (footballer)|James Howie]] {{goal|40||55}}\n | goals2 = {{goal|81}} [[Albert Shepherd]]\n | stadium = [[Hampden Park]], [[Glasgow]] \n | attendance = 102,741\n | referee = William Nunnerley ([[Football Association of Wales|Wales]])\n}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book\n|author= Guy Oliver\n|title=The Guinness Record of World Soccer\n|year=1992\n|publisher=Guinness\n|isbn = 0-85112-954-4 }}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{British Home Championship}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Home Championship}}\n[[Category:1906 in British sport]]\n[[Category:1905\u201306 in Welsh football|Brit]]\n[[Category:1905\u201306 in English football]]\n[[Category:1905\u201306 in Scottish football]]\n[[Category:British Home Championships|1905]]\n[[Category:1905\u201306 in Irish association football|Brit]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox international football competition\n|tourney_name=1905\u20131906 British Home Championship\n|image      =\n|size       =\n|caption    =\n|country    =England, Ireland, Scotland and Wales\n|dates      =17 February\u20137 April 1906\n|num_teams  =4\n|champion_other=Shared: {{fb|ENG}}/{{fb|SCO}}\n|attendance =\n|matches    =6\n|goals      =20\n|top_scorer ={{fbicon|WAL|1807}} [[William Green (footballer)|William Green]] and {{fbicon|IRE}} [[Harold Sloan]] {{nowrap|(3 goals)}}\n|prevseason =[[1901\u201302 British Home Championship|1901\u20131902]]\n|nextseason =[[1903\u201304 British Home Championship|1903\u201304]]\n}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\nThe '''1905\u201306 [[British Home Championship]]''' was the 22nd edition of the annual international [[football (soccer)|football]] tournament played between the British [[Home Nations]]. The trophy was shared between the two sides which regularly dominated the competition, [[England national football team|England]] and [[Scotland national football team|Scotland]] who each gained four points.\n\nEngland and [[Ireland national football team (1882\u20131950)|Ireland]] began the tournament in February 1906, with England scoring five goals without reply and rising to the head of the table. [[Wales national football team|Wales]] joined them after their match with Scotland which they won in [[Edinburgh]] 2\u20130. Scotland recovered to beat Ireland by a single goal and England then moved ahead by beating Wales with an identical scoreline. Playing for lower rankings, Wales and Ireland fought out a thrilling 4\u20134 draw in [[Cardiff]] before the deciding game between England and Scotland. England needed only a draw to take the trophy undisputed, but Scotland played well and in flowing match triumphed 2\u20131 to share the honours.\n\nParts of the Wales vs Ireland match at Wrexham were filmed by the Blackburn company of Mitchell and Kenyon, and is now the oldest surviving footage of an international football match.<ref>{{cite book |editor1-first=John |editor1-last=Davies|editor1-link=John Davies (historian)|editor2-first=Nigel |editor2-last=Jenkins | editor2-link=Nigel Jenkins| editor3-first=Baines |editor3-last=Menna|editor4-first=Peredur I. |editor4-last=Lynch|title=The Welsh Academy Encyclopaedia of Wales |year=2008 |publisher=University of Wales Press |location=Cardiff|page=282 |isbn=978-0-7083-1953-6}}</ref>\n\n==Table==\n<onlyinclude>{{#invoke:sports table|main|style=WDL\n|show_positions=n\n|winpoints=2\n\n|team1=ENG|name_ENG={{fb|ENG}}\n|team2=SCO|name_SCO={{fb|SCO}}\n|team3=WAL|name_WAL={{fb|WAL|1807}}\n|team4=IRE|name_IRE={{fb|IRE}}\n|win_ENG=2|draw_ENG=0|loss_ENG=1|gf_ENG=7|ga_ENG=2|status_ENG=C\n|win_SCO=2|draw_SCO=0|loss_SCO=1|gf_SCO=3|ga_SCO=3|status_SCO=C\n|win_WAL=1|draw_WAL=1|loss_WAL=1|gf_WAL=6|ga_WAL=5\n|win_IRE=0|draw_IRE=1|loss_IRE=2|gf_IRE=4|ga_IRE=10\n|status_text_C=Co-champions\n|col_C=#ccffcc|text_C=\n|result1=C|result2=C\n|update=complete|source=\n|class_rules = 1) points. The points system worked as follows: 2 points for a win and 1 point for a draw.\n}}</onlyinclude>\n\n==Results==\n{{football box \n | date = 17 February 1906\n | team1 = {{fb-rt|IRE}}\n | score = 0 \u2013 5\n | team2 = {{fb|ENG}}\n | goals1 = &nbsp; \n | goals2 = {{goal|26||89|}} [[Dicky Bond]] <br />{{goal|32}} [[Arthur Brown (footballer, born 1885)|Arthur Brown]] <br />{{goal|56}} [[Stanley Harris (footballer)|Stanley Harris]] <br />{{goal|70}} [[Samuel Day (sportsman)|Samuel Day]]\n | 