{"title_page": "Gadsden Mall", "text_new": "{{Infobox shopping mall\n| name              = Gadsden Mall\n| image             = Gadsden mall textlogo.png\n| caption           = \n| location          = [[Gadsden, Alabama]], United States\n| opening_date      = July 31, 1974<ref name=\"gt740731\">{{cite news |title=Mall's reception enthusiastic |first=George |last=Utler |newspaper=[[The Gadsden Times]] |location=Gadsden, AL |page=1 |date=July 31, 1974}}</ref>\n| closing_date      = \n| developer         = [[Colonial Properties]]<ref name=\"gt740731\"/>\n| manager           = [[Spinoso Real Estate Group]]\n| owner             = \n| number_of_stores  = 70+\n| number_of_anchors = 3 (2 open, 1 vacant)\n| floor_area        = {{convert|502591|sqft|m2}}<ref name=\"preit1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.preit.com/leasing/detail/plans/37 |title=Gadsden Mall - Plans |publisher=Pennsylvania Real Estate Investment Trust |accessdate=June 21, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809102624/http://preit.com/leasing/detail/plans/37 |archivedate=August 9, 2011 }}</ref>\n| floors            = 1\n| coordinates       = {{coord|33|59|44.12|N|86|0|26|W|type:landmark_region:US-AL|display=inline, title}}\n| website           = {{url|shopgadsdenmall.com}}\n}}\nThe '''Gadsden Mall''' is a regional {{convert|502591|sqft|m2|adj=on}} [[shopping mall]] on [[U.S. Route 411 in Alabama|U.S. Route 411]] (Rainbow Drive) in [[Gadsden, Alabama|Gadsden]], [[Alabama]]. Located at the interchange of [[Interstate 759]] and [[U.S. Route 411 in Alabama|U.S. Route 411]], it is in the southern section of the city. It is anchored by [[Belk]] and [[Sears]].\n\n==History==\nThe site of the mall was historically knowns as [[Flat (landform)|the flats]] near Barrel Springs.<ref>http://gadsdenmessenger.com/2016/03/25/the-vagabond-ringling-brothers-circus-first-came-to-gadsden-in-1899/</ref>\n\nSite preparation for the mall, the first mall in [[Etowah County]], began in September 1972, and construction started in March 1973.  Developed by Colonial Properties, the mall opened on July 31, 1974.<ref name=\"siteprep\">(12 July 2009). [http://www.gadsdentimes.com/opinion/20090712/shopping-trends-change-with-times Shopping trends change with times], ''Gadsden Times''</ref><ref name=\"40th\">Savage, Lisa (8 November 2015). [http://www.gadsdentimes.com/news/20151108/one-stop-shop-more-than-40-years-later-gadsden-mall-still-sees-success-in-business One-Stop Shop: More than 40 years later, Gadsden Mall still sees success in business], ''Gadsden Times''</ref>  [[Sears]] and [[Belk|Belk Hudson]] opened as anchors at the mall, leaving their downtown locations, as did some other downtown merchants.<ref name=\"siteprep\"/>\n\n[[JCPenney]] had a store in the mall from 1991-2001, and returned in 2008 in a new anchor location created as part of a remodeling of the mall. On March 17, 2017, it was announced that JCPenney would be closing as part of a plan to close 138 stores nationwide. The store closed on July 31, 2017.<ref name=\"gadsenjc\">Bailey, Greg (17 March 2017). [http://www.gadsdentimes.com/news/20170317/gadsdens-jcpenney-store-among-138-set-to-close Gadsden\u2019s JCPenney store among 138 set to close], ''Gadsden Times''</ref><ref name=\"40th\"/>\n\nOn October 15, 2018, it was announced that Sears would also be closing as part of a plan to close 142 stores nationwide which will leave Belk as the only anchor left.<ref>http://www.gadsdentimes.com/news/20181015/sears-store-at-gadsden-mall-to-close</ref>\n\n==Roy Moore==\nIn November 2017, the mall became a subject of widespread news reports regarding U.S. Senate candidate [[Roy Moore]], with reports that Moore used to frequent the mall in the early 1980s and would approach teenage females for dates, leading to locals claiming that Moore had been \"banned\" from the mall though no formal ban has been proven.<ref name=\"newyorker\">Bethea, Charles (13 November 2017). [https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/locals-were-troubled-by-roy-moores-interactions-with-teen-girls-at-the-gadsden-mall Locals were troubled by Roy Moore's interactions with teen girls at the Gadsden Mall], ''The New Yorker''</ref><ref name=\"vollers\">Vollers, Anna Claire (13 November 2017). [http://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2017/11/gadsden_residents_say_moores_b.html Gadsden locals say Moore's predatory behavior at mall, restaurants not a secret], ''[[The Birmingham News]]''</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.shopgadsdenmall.com Gadsden Mall official website]\n{{wide image|Sears - Gadsden Mall, Gadsden, Alabama.jpg|1000px|alt=Sears at Gadsden Mall|Sears at Gadsden Mall}} \n\n{{Shopping malls in Alabama}}\n\n[[Category:Shopping malls established in 1974]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Gadsden, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Etowah County, Alabama]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox shopping mall\n| name              = Gadsden Mall\n| image             = Gadsden mall textlogo.png\n| caption           = \n| location          = [[Gadsden, Alabama]], United States\n| opening_date      = July 31, 1974<ref name=\"gt740731\">{{cite news |title=Mall's reception enthusiastic |first=George |last=Utler |newspaper=[[The Gadsden Times]] |location=Gadsden, AL |page=1 |date=July 31, 1974}}</ref>\n| closing_date      = \n| developer         = [[Colonial Properties]]<ref name=\"gt740731\"/>\n| manager           = [[Spinoso Real Estate Group]]\n| owner             = \n| number_of_stores  = 70+\n| number_of_anchors = 3 (2 open, 1 vacant)\n| floor_area        = {{convert|502591|sqft|m2}}<ref name=\"preit1\">{{cite web|url=http://www.preit.com/leasing/detail/plans/37 |title=Gadsden Mall - Plans |publisher=Pennsylvania Real Estate Investment Trust |accessdate=June 21, 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110809102624/http://preit.com/leasing/detail/plans/37 |archivedate=August 9, 2011 }}</ref>\n| floors            = 1\n| coordinates       = {{coord|33|59|44.12|N|86|0|26|W|type:landmark_region:US-AL|display=inline, title}}\n| website           = {{url|shopgadsdenmall.com}}\n}}\nThe '''Gadsden Mall''' is a regional {{convert|502591|sqft|m2|adj=on}} [[shopping mall]] on [[U.S. Route 411 in Alabama|U.S. Route 411]] (Rainbow Drive) in [[Gadsden, Alabama|Gadsden]], [[Alabama]]. Located at the interchange of [[Interstate 759]] and [[U.S. Route 411 in Alabama|U.S. Route 411]], it is in the southern section of the city. It is anchored by [[Belk]] and [[Sears]].\n\n==History==\nThe site of the mall was historically knowns as [[Flat (landform)|the flats]] near Barrel Springs.<ref>http://gadsdenmessenger.com/2016/03/25/the-vagabond-ringling-brothers-circus-first-came-to-gadsden-in-1899/</ref>\n\nSite preparation for the mall, the first mall in [[Etowah County]], began in September 1972, and construction started in March 1973.  Developed by Colonial Properties, the mall opened on July 31, 1974.<ref name=\"siteprep\">(12 July 2009). [http://www.gadsdentimes.com/opinion/20090712/shopping-trends-change-with-times Shopping trends change with times], ''Gadsden Times''</ref><ref name=\"40th\">Savage, Lisa (8 November 2015). [http://www.gadsdentimes.com/news/20151108/one-stop-shop-more-than-40-years-later-gadsden-mall-still-sees-success-in-business One-Stop Shop: More than 40 years later, Gadsden Mall still sees success in business], ''Gadsden Times''</ref>  [[Sears]] and [[Belk|Belk Hudson]] opened as anchors at the mall, leaving their downtown locations, as did some other downtown merchants.<ref name=\"siteprep\"/>\n\n[[JCPenney]] had a store in the mall from 1991-2001, and returned in 2008 in a new anchor location created as part of a remodeling of the mall. On March 17, 2017, it was announced that JCPenney would be closing as part of a plan to close 138 stores nationwide. The store closed on July 31, 2017.<ref name=\"gadsenjc\">Bailey, Greg (17 March 2017). [http://www.gadsdentimes.com/news/20170317/gadsdens-jcpenney-store-among-138-set-to-close Gadsden\u2019s JCPenney store among 138 set to close], ''Gadsden Times''</ref><ref name=\"40th\"/>\n\nOn October 15, 2018, it was announced that Sears would also be closing as part of a plan to close 142 stores nationwide which will leave Belk as the only anchor left.<ref>http://www.gadsdentimes.com/news/20181015/sears-store-at-gadsden-mall-to-close</ref>\n\n==Roy Moore==\nIn November 2017, the mall became a subject of widespread news reports regarding U.S. Senate candidate [[Roy Moore]], with reports that Moore used to frequent the mall in the early 1980s and would approach teenage females for dates, leading to locals claiming that Moore had been \"banned\" from the mall though no formal ban has been proven.<ref name=\"newyorker\">Bethea, Charles (13 November 2017). [https://www.newyorker.com/news/news-desk/locals-were-troubled-by-roy-moores-interactions-with-teen-girls-at-the-gadsden-mall Locals were troubled by Roy Moore's interactions with teen girls at the Gadsden Mall], ''The New Yorker''</ref><ref name=\"vollers\">Vollers, Anna Claire (13 November 2017). [http://www.al.com/news/index.ssf/2017/11/gadsden_residents_say_moores_b.html Gadsden locals say Moore's predatory behavior at mall, restaurants not a secret], ''[[The Birmingham News]]''</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.shopgadsdenmall.com Gadsden Mall official website]\n{{wide image|Sears - Gadsden Mall, Gadsden, Alabama.jpg|1000px|alt=Sears at Gadsden Mall|Sears at Gadsden Mall}} \n\n{{Shopping malls in Alabama}}\n{{CBL Properties}}\n\n[[Category:Shopping malls established in 1974]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Alabama]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Gadsden, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Etowah County, Alabama]]\n", "name_user": "Thebisch", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removed CBL Properties Infobox (missed it last time)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gadsden_Mall"}
